{
  "result": "Every city has an hour that belongs only to it. In mine, that hour arrives just before sunrise, when delivery trucks whisper at red lights and apartment windows glow like lanterns over a harbor. I like to walk then, before the noise of intentions begins. The bakery on the corner opens first; warm air slips onto the sidewalk, carrying the smell of yeast, sugar, and yesterday forgiven.\n\nAt that time of day, details look honest. A cracked curb is simply a cracked curb, not a civic failure or a metaphor. A stray cat is only a cat, stretching in the blue light as if it invented morning. Even my own thoughts behave better. Problems shrink to manageable shapes, and ambitions stop shouting. I can hear the rhythm of my steps and remember that a life is built exactly this way: one small, ordinary motion repeated with attention.\n\nBy seven o\u2019clock, the spell breaks. Phones vibrate, buses hiss, headlines compete for outrage. Yet the quiet hour leaves a residue, a thin coat of patience I carry into meetings, errands, mistakes. It reminds me that urgency is often a costume, and that most important things\u2014friendship, craft, recovery, love\u2014grow slowly, like bread rising in a warm kitchen.\n\nMaybe that is why I keep walking at dawn. Not to escape the world, but to meet it before it puts on armor. On good days, I return home with cold hands and a heart, ready to begin again, less afraid of what the daylight demands.",
